```

The `load` function loads the saved workspace variables from the `Face.mat` file, including `F` and `L` that contain the facial images and their corresponding labels, respectively.

The `splitData` function takes `F` and `L` as inputs and returns four outputs: `trainData`, `testData`, `trainLabels` and `testLabels`. This function randomly splits the input data and labels into two sets: training and testing, with a default ratio of 70% training and 30% testing.

Here's an example implementation of the `splitData` function:

```matlab
function [trainData, testData, trainLabels, testLabels] = splitData(data, labels, ratio)
% splitData - split data and labels randomly into training and testing sets
% 
% Syntax: [trainData, testData, trainLabels, testLabels] = splitData(data, labels, ratio)
% 
% Inputs:
%   data - input data of size (N x D), where N is the number of samples and D is the number of features
%   labels - input labels of size (N x 1), where N is the number of samples
%   ratio (optional) - ratio of training set to testing set (default is 0.7)
% 
% Outputs:
%   trainData - training set data of size (M x D), where M is the number of training samples
%   testData - testing set data of size (N-M x D), where N is the total number of samples and D is the number of features
%   trainLabels - training set labels of size (M x 1), where M is the number of training samples
%   testLabels - testing set labels of size (N-M x 1), where N is the total number of samples

    if nargin < 3
        ratio = 0.7; % default ratio of 70% training and 30% testing
    end

    % get unique labels and count of each label
    uniqueLabels = unique(labels);
    labelCounts = accumarray(labels, 1);

    trainData = [];
    testData = [];
    trainLabels = [];
    testLabels = [];

    % randomly split data for each unique label
    for i = 1:length(uniqueLabels)
        label = uniqueLabels(i);
        dataIdxs = find(labels == label);
        data = data(dataIdxs, :);
        n = size(data, 1);
        permIdxs = randperm(n);
        cutoff = round(ratio * n);
        trainData = [trainData; data(permIdxs(1:cutoff), :)];
        testData = [testData; data(permIdxs(cutoff+1:end), :)];
        trainLabels = [trainLabels; repmat(label, cutoff, 1)];
        testLabels = [testLabels; repmat(label, n-cutoff, 1)];
    end
end
```

The `splitData` function uses the `randperm` function to randomly permute the indices of each label's data, and then selects a part of them as training data and the remaining part as testing data.

You can adjust the `ratio` input to specify the desired split ratio between training and testing sets.

